Twitter US Airline Sentiment - Connie Ullas¶

Problem Definition and Information¶

Context¶

Sentiment analysis/classification, which involves monitoring emotions in conversations on social media platforms, has become a key strategy in social media marketing. Twitter is one social media company that possesses 330 million monthly active users and produces a lot of data through tweets. Listening to how customers feel about the product/service on Twitter allows companies to understand their audience, keep on top of what is being said about their brand and their competitors, and discover new trends in the industry.

Objective¶

Given a tweet, build a Natural Language Processing model that can determine whether a tweet is positive, negative, or neutral.

Key Questions¶

  1. Is there a good NLP model to predict a customer's sentiment in a tweet?
  2. What are the key words that determine a customer's sentiment?
  3. What improvements can airlines make to keep customers positive?

Data Information¶

Twitter data on airlines was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service"). A detailed data dictionary can be found below.

Data Dictionary

  • tweet_id
  • airline_sentiment
  • airline_sentiment_confidence
  • negativereason
  • negativereason_confidence
  • airline
  • airline_sentiment_gold
  • name
  • negativereason_gold
  • retweet_count
  • text
  • tweet_coord
  • tweet_created
  • tweet_location
  • user_timezone

# function to create labeled barplots

def labeled_barplot(data, feature, feature2=None, perc=False, n=None, size=12,height=5):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, height))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, height))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
        hue=feature2,
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=size,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# string pre-processing
def strip_html(text):
    """Remove HTML tags in string of text"""
    soup = BeautifulSoup(text, "html.parser")
    return soup.get_text()

def replace_contractions(text):
    """Replace contractions in string of text"""
    return contractions.fix(text)

def remove_numbers(text):
    """Remove numbers in string of text"""
    text = re.sub(r'\d+', '', text)
    return text

def remove_mentions(text):
    """Remove mentions from list of tokenized words"""
    text = re.sub("@[A-Za-z0-9]+","",text)
    return text

def clean_text(text):
    text = strip_html(text)
    text = replace_contractions(text)
    text = remove_numbers(text)
    text = remove_mentions(text)
    return text

df1['text'] = df1['text'].apply(lambda x: clean_text(x))

# Defining stopwords
stopwords_list = stopwords.words('english')

customlist = ['not', "couldn't", 'didn', "didn't", 'doesn', "doesn't", 'hadn', "hadn't", 'hasn',
        "hasn't", 'haven', "haven't", 'isn', "isn't", 'ma', 'mightn', "mightn't", 'mustn',
        "mustn't", 'needn', "needn't", 'shan', "shan't", 'shouldn', "shouldn't", 'wasn',
        "wasn't", 'weren', "weren't", 'won', "won't", 'wouldn', "wouldn't"]

# Set custom stopwords list as not, couldn't etc. Words matter in Sentiment, so not removing them from original data.

stopwords_list = list(set(stopwords_list) - set(customlist))
In [30]:
# pre-processing steps
def remove_non_ascii(words):
    """Remove non-ASCII characters from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', word).encode('ascii', 'ignore').decode('utf-8', 'ignore')
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

def remove_punctuation(words):
    """Remove punctuation from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', word)
        if new_word != '':
            new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

def remove_stopwords(words):
    """Remove stop words from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
      if word not in stopwords_list:
            new_words.append(word)
    return new_words

def to_lowercase(words):
    """Convert all characters to lowercase from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        if word not in stopwords_list:
            new_words.append(word)
    return new_words

# apply lemmatization
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
def lemmatize_list(words):
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
      new_words.append(lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos='v'))
    return new_words

# bring all functions together
def normalize(words):
    words = remove_non_ascii(words)
    words = remove_punctuation(words)
    words = to_lowercase(words)
    words = remove_stopwords(words)
    words = lemmatize_list(words)
    return ' '.join(words)

df1['text'] = df1.apply(lambda row: normalize(row['text']), axis=1)

# plotting the error as k increases
error = [1 - x for x in cv_scores]                                 #error corresponds to each nu of estimator
optimal_learners = base_ln[error.index(min(error))]                #Selection of optimal nu of n_estimator corresponds to minimum error.
plt.plot(base_ln, error)                                           #Plot between each nu of estimator and misclassification error
xy = (optimal_learners, min(error))
plt.annotate('(%s, %s)' % xy, xy = xy, textcoords='data')
plt.xlabel("Number of base learners")
plt.ylabel("Misclassification Error")
plt.show()

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))

subjects = ['Count_Vectorizer', 'TF-IDF']

ax.bar(subjects,scores)
ax.set_ylabel('scores',fontsize= 12)    # y axis label
ax.set_xlabel('models',fontsize= 12)    # x axis label
ax.set_title('Accuaracies of Supervised Learning Methods')  # tittle
for i, v in enumerate(scores):
    ax.text( i ,v+0.01, '{:.2f}%'.format(100*v), color='black', fontweight='bold')
    plt.savefig('barplot_1.png',dpi=100, format='png', bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()
  • The results are similar for both models.
  • TF-IDF shows a better performance than Count Vectorizer, because it not only focuses on the frequency of words present in the corpus but also provides the importance of the words. We can then remove the words that are less important for analysis, hence making the model building less complex by reducing the input dimensions.

Part 5: Summary and Recommendations¶

Data Background:

  • There are 14640 rows and 15 columns in the data.
  • There are 36 duplicated rows in the data.
  • The columns airline_sentiment and text are object type.

Data Preprocessing:

  • Dropped 36 duplicate rows.
  • Only kept the airline_sentiment and text columns for analysis.
  • Cleaned text data: remove HTML tags, replace contractions, remove numbers, remove mentions, tokenization, remove special characters, remove punctuation, lowercase, remove stopwords, lemmatization,

Observations from EDA:

  • United Airlines tweets make up the largest share (26%) of the tweets and Virgin America has the least number of tweets (3.5%).
  • A majority (62.7%) of tweets are negative, followed by neutral and positive. The data is imbalanced.
  • United, US Airways, and American have much more negative than positive tweets (difference of greater than 55%).
  • Southwest and Delta are more balanced between negative and positive tweets (difference of less than 26%).
  • All airlines except Delta have "Customer Service Issue" as their main negative reason. Delta has it as its second reason.
  • All airlines had a negative reason related to the flight in their top 2 either with a late flight, cancelled flight, or a flight booking.
  • Damaged luggage and long lines were the least likely to be negative reasons across all airlines.
  • Outside of the airline names, the hour, late flight, hold, waiting, still, delay were some of the important recurring words observed in the negative tweets.
  • Outside of the airline names, the great, love, much, thank, appreciate, good, amazing were some of the important recurring words observed in the positive tweets.

Vectorization, Model Building and Performance:

  • Data was split into train (70%) test (30%) sets.
  • The pre-processed data is converted to numbers (vectorized), so that we can feed the data into the model.
  • Random Forest classifier was built on the data. Count Vectorizer showed a 76.8% accuracy on the test data. TF-IDF vectorizer showed a 77.9% accuracy on the test data. Both models did not overfit.
  • All metrics are the highest for negative tweets and lowest for neutral tweets. It is easier for the model to classify a positive or negative sentiment than a neutral one.
  • In supervised learning techniques, TF-IDF outperforms BoW since it not only considers the frequency of words in the corpus but also considers their importance.
  • TFIDF technique was able to give improved f1 scores for negative and neutral tweets. The f1 score for positive tweets was low compared to the f1 score given by the model through bag of words vectors.

Recommendations¶

  • Customers are more likely to tweet when they feel negatively than positively.
  • Airlines should focus on improving customer service issues. More research into the data on what the exact customer issues are can improve positive sentiment.
  • Airlines should focus on minimizing cancellation and delay of flights.
  • Airlines can focus less on problems due to luggage or long lines.
  • Words of appreciation were the top words for positive sentiment tweets. Airlines should focus on compensation for customers or offering rewards when appropriate.
  • It is recommended to train the model with more balanced data such as using oversampling or undersampling techniques to improve performance on positive sentiment tweets.
  • We can still increase the accuracy of our model by increasing the max_feature parameter in the vectorizer.
  • We can apply other model tuning and hyperparameter tuning techniques, as well as other pre-processing techniques to increase the overall accuracy even further.
